extbraceright{} \textbraceleft 2\textbraceright\textbackslash,\textbraceleft (\textbackslash rho \textasciicircum\textbraceleft\textbackslash prime\textbraceright )\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft 2\textbraceright\textbraceleft\textbackslash left [\textbackslash frac\textbraceleft\textbraceleft\textbackslash partial \textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft 2\textbraceright p\textbraceright{} \textbraceleft\textbackslash partial \textbraceleft\textbackslash rho \textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft 2\textbraceright\textbraceright\textbackslash right ]\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft S\textbraceright{} + \textbackslash cdots \textbackslash,\&\textbackslash end\textbraceleft array\textbraceright\$\$and for convenience we define the quantity 2.4\$\$\textbraceleft c\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft 2\textbraceright{} \textbackslash equiv \textbraceleft\textbackslash left [\textbackslash frac\textbraceleft\textbackslash partial p\textbraceright{} \textbraceleft\textbackslash partial \textbackslash rho \textbraceright\textbackslash right ]\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft S\textbraceright,\$\$where c will turn out to be the speed of sound in an ideal fluid. In the above equations, {$\rho$} is the density, v the particle velocity, p the pressure, and the subscript S denotes that the thermodynamic partial derivatives are taken at constant entropy. The ambient quantities of the quiescent (time independent) medium are identified by the subscript 0. We use small perturbations for the pressure and density, p\,=\,p0\,+\,p{$\prime$}, {$\rho$}\,=\,{$\rho$}0\,+\,{$\rho\prime$}, and note that v is also a small quantity; that is, the particle velocity which results from density and pressure perturbations is much smaller than the speed of sound.},
