  urldate = {2021-07-20},
  abstract = {{$<$}section class="abstract"{$><$}h2 class="abstractTitle text-title my-1" id="d13789349e56"{$>$}Abstract{$<$}/h2{$><$}p{$>$}In tropical regions, and for applications where the alongshore scale {$<$}em{$>$}k{$<$}/em{$>$}\textsuperscript{-1} of the forcing is large, the assumption of constant Coriolis parameters {$<$}em{$>$}f{$<$}/em{$>$} in Csanady's Arrested Topographic Wave (ATW) model is invalid. Here we generalize the ATW model for study wind-driven coastal circulation by allowing {$<$}em{$>$}f{$<$}/em{$>$} to vary according to the {$\beta$}-plane approximation {$<$}em{$>$}f{$<$}/em{$>$} = \textsubscript{0} + {$\beta<$}em{$>$}y{$<$}/em{$>$}, and by deriving solutions for finite width shelves. Bottom friction is assumed to be linear in the depth-averaged velocity with coefficient {$<$}em{$>$}r{$<$}/em{$>$} and the depth {$<$}em{$>$}h{$<$}/em{$>$}({$<$}em{$>$}x{$<$}/em{$>$}) = {$<$}em{$>$}sx{$<$}/em{$>$} is assumed to increase linearly with distance {$<$}em{$>$}x{$<$}/em{$>$} offshore. The generalization includes the ATW solutions as a subset; however, theoretical and numerical calculations show that the dimensionless parameter {$\beta$}/{$<$}em{$>$}f{$<$}/em{$>$}\textsubscript{0}{$<$}em{$>$}k{$<$}/em{$>$} plays a key role in the flow structure. In particular, for infinitely wide shelves and nonzero values of {$\beta$}/{$<$}em{$>$}f{$<$}/em{$>$}\textsubscript{0}{$<$}em{$>$}k{$<$}/em{$>$}, enhanced trapping occurs for coastal circulation off an east cost while trapped solutions cease to exist for circulation off a west coast. For finite width shelves, specification of zero sea level anomaly at the shelf break allows solutions for wind-driven circulation on both eat and west costs. Inclusion of the {$\beta$} effect results in a smaller trapping scale for coastal flows on east coasts (western ocean boundaries) and a larger trapping scale for coastal flows on west coasts. Asymptotic solutions for geographically varying wind stress with oscillatory form are presented as examples.{$<$}/p{$><$}/section{$>$}},
